HEADWORD: Spheroid
<hw>Sphe"roid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>spheroides</ets> ball-like, spherical, Gr. <?/<?/<?/; <?/<?/<?/<?/
sphere + <grk>e'i^dos</grk> form: cf. F.
<ets>sph⟦eacute⟧ro⟦ium⟧de</ets>.]</ety> <def>A body or figure
approaching to a sphere, but not perfectly spherical; esp., a solid
generated by the revolution of an ellipse about one of its
axes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Oblate spheroid</b></col>, <col><b>Prolate
